(56, 2, 0, 'Sneak Peek Trailer for the Upcoming Novel, "The Sixth Station" by New York Post columnist, Linda Stasi', '', '2012-11-19 00:00:00', '2013-02-01 14:32:49', '<p class="p1">Alessandra Russo is a fugitive-at-large, running from powerful government leaders after being wrongly affiliated with the world''s most dangerous terrorist -- and then being accused of murder. But, the thing is, she is innocent.</p>\r\n<p class="p1">In other words, Alessandra Russo is exactly the kind of client that would seek out the services of Davidoff Hutcher &amp; Citron!</p>\r\n<p class="p1">Therefore, our firm is very pleased to give our clients the first sneak peek trailer for the upcoming (and we believe) blockbuster novel, "The Sixth Station" by DH&amp;C family member, New York Post columnist, Linda Stasi.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class="p1">Number one Best Selling Authors such as Nelson DeMille hail it as "Great writing," while Steve Berry of "The Templar Legacy" says, "You''ll be gripping the pages so tight, your knuckles will turn white," and Linda Fairstein, former NYC sex crimes prosecutor and author of "Night Watch," raves,"Smart, intriguing, irreverent."</p>\r\n<p class="p1">If you like the trailer, share it with your friends, if you love it, pre-order the book from Amazon, Barnes &amp; Nobel, or Walmart.</p>\r\n<p class="p1"><img src="../img/The-Sixth-Station.jpg" alt="" /></p>\r\n<p class="p3"><span class="s1">View the trailer here: <a>http://vimeo.com/52296787</a></span></p>\r\n<p class="p3"><span class="s1"><span class="s2"><a href="../../../index/The-Sixth-Station-s-Book-Signing">See pictures from the Book Signing Event at Davidoff Hutcher &amp; Citron LLP</a><br /></span></span></p>', 'Law', 0x536e65616b205065616b, 0, 1, 1, 1, 'Sneak-Peek-Trailer-for-the-Upcoming-Novel,-"The-Sixth-Station"-by-New-York-Post-columnist,-Linda-Stasi', 0, ''),
(63, 2, 0, 'Year End Estate Planning Techniques', '', '2012-12-04 00:00:00', '2012-12-17 07:00:38', '<p><span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Toward the end of each year we like to advise our clients regarding what they may wish to do before year end and what they should plan for the coming year. We have set out below techniques for gift giving and other techniques you may use without incurring any gift tax. Many of these techniques will also reduce your overall income tax burden.</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Consider making non-taxable gifts in excess of the annual exclusion using your federal gift tax exclusion of $5.12 Million ($10.24 Million for married couples). This gifting opportunity is part of a tax law that is scheduled to expire at the end of the year and will without further action by congress revert to $1 Million on January 1, 2013. This is the largest gift tax exemption - and opportunity - in history. To take advantage of the opportunity, you may consider outright gifts or gifts in a trust including trusts for your grandchildren''s education. Gifts can be made with real estate, stock or other assets. Any gifts above the annual gift tax exclusion will require filing a gift tax return even if no tax is due.</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Gifts in Trust</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>Despite the tax savings, you may be uneasy about making outright gifts to your children or grandchildren, due to your loss of control over how they use the gift. This concern can be addressed by making the gifts in trust, which will allow you to determine when they receive the money and how it is to be used.</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>There are special requirements for ensuring that a gift in trust qualifies for the annual exclusion. Usually, the trust is drafted to provide the beneficiary with temporary withdrawal rights over the gift (usually for 30 days), such that it is considered a present interest rather than one that vests in the future. Although this presents a risk of the beneficiary withdrawing the gift from the trust, the probability of your terminating any further gifts to the trust is usually sufficient to prevent this. If you are interested in making a gift in trust, we will be glad to explain how this can be done.</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Charitable Gifts</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>The year end is a good time to review your charitable giving to ensure that it is being done in the most tax-efficient manner. Charitable giving is a form of estate planning, because a gift to charity will never be subject to estate or gift tax appreciated assets also give you a chance to avoid capital gains by gifting appreciated stock with a low basis. If your are planning to make a large gift before January 1st, you should review its impact on your 2012 income tax liability and whether it may make sense to defer all or a portion of the gift to 2013. If the gift is of property and will require an appraisal (usually required for gifts of property with a value in excess of $5,000.00, other than publicly traded stock), we should start the process as soon as possible so that the appraisal is available before year end.</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>In conclusion, we hope that the information in this letter is useful in your year-end gift planning. If you wish to take advantage of any of the planning techniques that we have described, please feel free to call.</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Sincerely yours,</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em>Howard Presant&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; and&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; Michael G. Zapson </em></p>\r\n<p>646-428-3282&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 516-247-4431<em> </em></p>', 'Estate Planning, Gifts in Trust, ', '', 0, 1, 1, 1, 'Year-End-Estate-Planning-Techniques', 0, ''),
(64, 2, 0, 'Robert Lewis Promoted to Senior Counsel', '', '2012-12-14 00:00:00', '2013-02-13 20:13:34', '<p>NEW YORK &ndash; December 14, 2012 &ndash; Davidoff Hutcher &amp; Citron LLP, one of New York''s top law and government affairs firms, today announced that Robert J. Lewis has been promoted by the firm to Senior Counsel, having served the firm as an Associate since October 2010.&nbsp;&nbsp; Mr. Lewis was selected as one of the Top 40 Family Lawyers Under 40 in the State of New York for 2013 by the American Society of Legal Advocates.&nbsp; Mr. Lewis is recognized for his &ldquo;exceptional legal talent and early promise among the next generation of great lawyers.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>During his time at Davidoff Hutcher &amp; Citron, Mr. Lewis has garnered several awards and accolades, including being recognized by <em>Ten Leaders</em> as one of the top ten attorneys in New York under the age of 45 in the practice area of matrimonial and divorce law; inclusion in <em>Super Lawyers (Rising Stars Edition)</em> as one of the best Family Law attorneys in New York; the Top Attorneys &ndash; New York Metro Area&rsquo;s Outstanding Young Lawyers LIST in the field of Family Law; and as a Legal Expert on Family Law and relationships for two television shows.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Robert&rsquo;s presence and growth over the last two years has brought renown and recognition in an important practice area for us,&rdquo; said Jeffrey Citron, Davidoff Hutcher &amp; Citron&rsquo;s Co-Managing Partner. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re delighted to count him as a new Senior Counsel, and are exceedingly proud of the latest in a long string of accolades.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Prior to joining Davidoff Hutcher &amp; Citron, Lewis, 35, worked as a Matrimonial and Family Law Associate in the offices of Malcolm S. Taub LLP.&nbsp; He is admitted to practice law in New York, as well as in the United States District Courts for the Southern and Eastern Districts of New York. He is a member of the American Bar Association, Family Law Section; The New York State Bar Association, Family Law Section; and the Association of the Bar of the City of New York. Lewis holds a Juris Doctor from the Benjamin N. Cardozo School of Law, Class of 2002, where he has also taught legal writing, with an emphasis on Matrimonial and Family Law and was a member of the Journal of Conflict Resolution.&nbsp; He holds a bachelor&rsquo;s degree from the University of Rochester, with distinction.</p>\r\n<p>Davidoff Hutcher &amp; Citron LLP <a href="dhclegal.com">www.dhclegal.com</a>, which has 48 attorneys in offices in New York City, Albany, Washington D.C., and Garden City, Long Island, provides legal and government relations services for a varied clientele that include Fortune 500 companies, financial institutions, prominent real estate organizations, developers, leading health and educational institutions, associations and services organizations, as well as other industries throughout the greater metropolitan area.</p>\r\n<p align="center"># # #</p>', 'ny family law attorney', '', 0, 1, 2, 1, 'Robert-Lewis-Promoted-to-Senior-Counsel', 0, '');

