(81, 2, 0, 'DHC Partner Dave Denenberg to host forum for residents who experienced flooding during Sandy', '', '2013-01-28 00:00:00', '2013-06-26 08:00:27', '<p><span class="userContent">Nassau County Legis. and DHC partner Dave Denenberg (D-Merrick) will host a community meeting Monday night for residents who experienced flooding issues during Sandy due to storm drain problems.</span></p>\r\n<p><span class="userContent">&nbsp;<a href="http://bit.ly/122nFT7">http://bit.ly/122nFT7</a></span></p>\r\n<p><span class="userContent"><br /></span></p>', 'Hurricane Sandy', '', 0, 1, 1, 1, 'DHC-Partner-Dave-Denenberg-to-host-forum-for-residents-who-experienced-flooding-during-Sandy', 0, ''),
(24, 2, 0, 'THOMAS MOHEN JOINS DAVIDOFF HUTCHER & CITRON LLP', '', '2012-02-28 00:00:00', '2012-11-28 23:37:45', '<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Davidoff Hutcher &amp; Citron LLP, one of New York''s top law and government relations firms, is pleased to announce that Thomas P. Mohen has joined the firm as Partner, effective August 1, 2012. Mr. Mohen will work from the Manhattan and Garden City, Long Island offices and continue his more than 25 year practice in the areas of general business matters, employment law and high-stakes commercial litigation.</p>\r\n<p>http://dmlegal.gardedev.com/app/webroot/img/attornyes/at92-838-taub.jpg</p>', 'updated keywords', 0x75706461746564206465736372697074696f6e, 0, 10, 2, 1, 'THOMAS-MOHEN-JOINS-DAVIDOFF-HUTCHER-and-CITRON-LLP', 0, ''),
(25, 2, 0, 'DAVIDOFF MALITO & HUTCHER LLP RENAMED AS DAVIDOFF HUTCHER & CITRON LLP ', '', '2012-02-28 00:00:00', '2012-10-27 12:11:49', '<p>Davidoff Malito &amp; Hutcher LLP, one of New York''s top law and government affairs firms, announced today it has changed its name to Davidoff Hutcher &amp; Citron LLP.</p>\r\n<p>"We are very pleased to announce the change in our firm''s name to add Jeff Citron," said Sid Davidoff, who Co-Founded the firm in 1975. "Larry Hutcher and Jeff have done a superb job as Co-Managing Partners for a number of years and now our new name reflects their efforts."</p>', 'test', 0x74657374, 0, 101, 2, 1, 'DAVIDOFF-MALITO---HUTCHER-LLP-RENAMED-AS-DAVIDOFF-HUTCHER---CITRON-LLP-', 0, ''),
(30, 3, 0, 'About The Firm', '', '2012-03-01 06:35:47', '2012-11-05 16:12:12', '<p>Davidoff Hutcher &amp; Citron LLP, founded in 1975, has become one of New York''s most respected mid-size commercial law and government relations firms. The firm has melded its multi-discipline law practice, with its distinguished government relations practice. We handle legal and lobbying matters from the routine to the complex. Each of our practice groups is chaired by a highly-distinguished lawyer in the field. We invite you to review the practice areas of particular interest to you.</p>\r\n<p>We practice law in a highly synergistic manner - - lawyers from different departments work together to achieve our clients'' objectives. We are known to be aggressive and results-oriented lawyers.</p>\r\n<p>Our skilled attorneys handle complicated and sensitive matters for a varied clientele that includes Fortune 500 companies, entrepreneurs, litigants in business disputes, financial institutions, owners of valuable intellectual property, prominent real estate owners and developers, individuals and families confronted with family law issues, leaders in the health industry, hospitality business owners, and well-known companies and executives in the fashion industry.</p>\r\n<p>With offices located in New York City, Albany, Washington, D.C., and on Long Island, our government relations group can closely monitor legislative and regulatory developments. This ability strengthens the value of our traditional legal services when clients'' legal matters intersect, as they often do, with governmental concerns. The firm''s experience in both government relations and traditional legal services enables us to address each client''s specific concerns with a perspective approach offered by few New York law firms.</p>\r\n<p>Our mid-size firm offers all the benefits of big firm practice with the advantages of small firm attention to detail and personalized service. We believe that our size and structure enables us to render services in a cost-effective and efficient manner. We keep our client''s financial needs in mind at all times.</p>\r\n<p>Please contact us with any questions you have about the firm.</p>\r\n<p>We look forward to working with you!</p>', 'Firm Profile', 0x4669726d2050726f66696c65, 0, 0, 0, 1, 'Firm-Profile', 2, ''),
(38, 3, 0, 'Law Practice Areas', '', '2012-03-29 04:06:34', '2013-08-12 08:15:03', '<p>Davidoff Hutcher &amp; Citron LLP is known for its in-depth and breadth of experience in assisting clients with their New York legal and lobbying needs. We offer a multi-discipline approach to address each client''s specific needs. Our practice areas include:</p>\r\n<div class="gray-content-container">\r\n<div class="practice-areas-grid">\r\n<div class="practice-area-col">\r\n<h3><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Administrative-Law">Administrative Law</a></h3>\r\n<p>Our administrative lawyers counsel and assist clients in virtually every aspect of administrative law, from obtaining licensing and permits to zoning and land use issues. With our firm''s extensive government relations experience, we work promptly and effectively with State and Federal governmental and regulatory agencies to achieve our clients'' business objectives. We also have vast experience counseling and representing clients with New York City Administrative Code and New York Codes, Rules and Regulation matters. From compliance and enforcement to violation proceeding we have experience working with virtually every kind of business and industry in New York City, Albany and Long Island.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Administrative-Law">Visit this practice area</a></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="practice-area-col">\r\n<h3><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Administrative-Law">Art Law</a></h3>\r\n<p>Davidoff Hutcher &amp; Citron LLP has vast experience in both Art Transactions and Art Litigation practice areas. Davidoff Hutcher &amp; Citron LLP has represented dealers, purchasers and artists in all types of art transactions. Additionally, Davidoff Hutcher &amp; Citron LLP has represented purchasers and dealers in countless litigations. Recently, Davidoff Hutcher &amp; Citron LLP obtained the dismissal of a $66 Million lawsuit brought against a dealer who was alleged to having sold over 500 alleged forged artworks.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Administrative-Law">Visit this practice area</a></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="practice-area-col-last">\r\n<h3><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Bankruptcy,-Restructuring-and-Creditors-Rights">Bankruptcy Law</a></h3>\r\n<p>Our New York bankruptcy lawyers are well positioned to advise and provide legal services on every aspect of our clients'' financial needs. This includes Chapter 7 bankruptcy liquidation and Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization. We handle all aspects of bankruptcy law for individuals, businesses, investors, creditors, vendors and other parties involved. We also litigate and negotiate, whenever possible, to resolve bankruptcy matters promptly and effectively for our clients.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Bankruptcy,-Restructuring-and-Creditors-Rights">Visit this practice area</a></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="practice-areas-grid">\r\n<div class="practice-area-col">\r\n<h3><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Commercial-Banking-and-Finance-Law">Commercial Banking &amp; <br /> Finance Law</a></h3>\r\n<p>Our commercial litigation lawyers represent individuals and public and private companies of all sizes, both domestic and foreign, across many industries on a variety of subject matters. Our litigation lawyers regularly handle sophisticated and complex litigation matters in a variety of State and Federal court venues in New York and across the nation, as well as in alternative dispute resolution forums, arbitration panels and administrative agency hearings. Our litigators routinely handle sensitive, high profile matters that place a premium on clients'' privacy and confidentiality. Our reputation as aggressive, effective litigators is best illustrated by the frequent referrals we receive from the opponents with whom we have litigated.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Commercial-Banking-and-Finance-Law">Visit this practice area</a></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="practice-area-col">\r\n<h3><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Commercial-Litigation">Commercial Litigation</a></h3>\r\n<p>Our commercial litigation lawyers represent individuals and public and private companies of all sizes, both domestic and foreign, across many industries on a variety of subject matters. Our litigation lawyers regularly handle sophisticated and complex litigation matters in a variety of State and Federal court venues in New York and across the nation, as well as in alternative dispute resolution forums, arbitration panels and administrative agency hearings. Our litigators routinely handle sensitive, high profile matters that place a premium on clients'' privacy and confidentiality. Our reputation as aggressive, effective litigators is best illustrated by the frequent referrals we receive from the opponents with whom we have litigated.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Commercial-Litigation">Visit this practice area</a></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="practice-area-col-last">\r\n<h3><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Construction-Law">Construction Law</a></h3>\r\n<p>Our construction lawyers have vast experience in all phases of the construction cycle and New York construction law. With a multi-departmental group of lawyers experienced in real estate, administrative, corporate, government relations, bankruptcy, land use, litigation, and outdoor advertising, we are well equipped to assist clients with meeting all their business, financial and litigation objectives. Our lawyers know how to manage and address disputes from their inception to completion. We provide clients with strategic counsel to overcome roadblocks and achieve construction goals in an efficient and cost-effective manner.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Construction-Law">Visit this practice area</a></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="clear">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class="practice-areas-grid">\r\n<div class="practice-area-col-last">\r\n<h3><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Corporate-Law">Corporate Law</a></h3>\r\n<p>Our corporate lawyers counsel entrepreneurs and public and private companies of all sizes, both domestic and foreign, on all of their legal business needs. We cater to the needs of our clients, from mergers and acquisitions and securities work, to financing, joint ventures and sales, to all commercial agreements and legal documentation. We also counsel and advise our clients on corporate governance and regulatory compliance from SEC regulations and requirements to Financial Industry Regulatory Authority (FINRA) requirements.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Corporate-Law">Visit this practice area</a></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="practice-area-col">\r\n<h3><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Divorce-and-Family-Law">Divorce &amp; Family Law</a></h3>\r\n<p>Our divorce &amp; family lawyers understand the complexity of personal life changes. We put contingency plans and agreements in place to make unforeseen transitions easier for all involved. Our attorneys also assist when situations and circumstances require a parting of ways. We take the time to understand our clients'' personal situations and protect their rights while helping them navigate through divorce proceedings or other family matters. We pride ourselves on being available when our clients need us most. We understand the impact that divorce and other family matters have on everyone involved, and work promptly and discretely to resolve them.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Divorce-and-Family-Law">Visit this practice area</a></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="practice-area-col-last">\r\n<h3><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Employment-Law">Employment Law</a></h3>\r\n<p>Our employment lawyers counsel management of companies of all sizes on labor and employment compliance issues at both the State and Federal level. We provide training and assist with the establishment of employment policies and procedures, and a comprehensive employee handbook that clearly defines the roles, responsibilities and rights of all employees. We also counsel and advise our clients on executive and employee compensation, employee benefits, and leaves of absence, as well as Equal Employee Opportunity, Affirmative Action, workplace safety and training and disability accommodation. We also have vast litigation experience in the courts, alternative dispute resolution forums and arbitration panels, as well in administrative agency hearings.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Employment-Law">Visit this practice area</a></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="clear">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class="practice-areas-grid">\r\n<div class="practice-area-col-last">\r\n<h3><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Fashion-Industry-Law">Fashion Industry Law</a></h3>\r\n<p>Our fashion lawyers are world renowned for meeting the New York legal needs of the fashion industry, from entrepreneurs and established international companies to investors and the firms that serve them. We represent fashion clients at all levels with a variety of services, from business formation to day-to-day operational issues to licensing to global intellectual property protection and mergers and acquisitions. Unlike boutique fashion law firms, we have a multidisciplinary group of lawyers that work promptly and effectively to meet fashion clients'' business objectives.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Fashion-Industry-Law">Visit this practice area</a></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="practice-area-col">\r\n<h3><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Government-Relations">Government Relations</a></h3>\r\n<p>Our government relations practice is at the cross-roads of legislation and business law. For over forty years, clients have come to us to learn how proposed bills, agency rules and legislation will potentially impact their businesses, and seek assistance in dealing with such matters. We excel at assisting New York business owners in obtaining proper permits, licensing and zoning to meet their business objectives. Our lawyers and lobbying staff understand how to navigate applications and issues through the legislative and executive branches to achieve meaningful results promptly.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Government-Relations">Visit this practice area</a></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="practice-area-col-last">\r\n<h3><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Health-Law">Health Law</a></h3>\r\n<p>Our New York healthcare practice group is well positioned to advise and provide legal services in every aspect of our clients'' business in the healthcare industry. This includes practice formation and transactions, day-to-day operations and employment matters, compliance with health laws and other regulations, accreditation and licensing to regulatory defense, litigation and alternative dispute resolution. With a multi-departmental group of attorneys with administrative, corporate, government relations, employment, bankruptcy, litigation, construction, trusts and estates experience, we offer an expertise that few other New York law firms can offer.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Health-Law">Visit this practice area</a></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="clear">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class="practice-areas-grid">\r\n<div class="practice-area-col">\r\n<h3><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Intellectual-Property">Intellectual Property</a></h3>\r\n<p>Our New York intellectual property lawyers assist clients with all their legal needs from patent and trademark searches and applications before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office, to due diligence, licensing and portfolio analysis. We represent both domestic and international businesses with foreign applications and trademark and patent opinion services. We have vast litigation experience with copyright, patent and trademark rights and infringement matters throughout the U.S. in both State and Federal courts. We also represent our clients in alternative dispute resolution forums and arbitration panels.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Intellectual-Property">Visit this practice area</a></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="practice-area-col">\r\n<h3><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Insurance-Litigation-Law">Insurance Litigation Law</a></h3>\r\n<p>Davidoff Hutcher &amp; Citron&rsquo;s attorneys have extensive knowledge and experience representing policy holders in disputes with their insurers. Having the full availability of the top litigators in New York, we aggressively pursue our clients&rsquo; interests.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Insurance-Litigation-Law">Visit this practice area</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="practice-area-col-last">\r\n<h3><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Land-Use">Land Use</a></h3>\r\n<p>Our land use lawyers advise clients on every aspect of how New York City and Long Island local zoning and building codes regulate the use and development of property they own or are looking to purchase. We do it all, from representing all parties involved in the development of land including buyers, sellers, investors, lenders and public authorities. Our years of experience, strong local government relationships and knowledge of the New York City and Long Island real estate marketplace allows us to provide our clients valuable legal counsel and guidance second to none.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Land-Use">Visit this practice area</a></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="clear">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class="practice-areas-grid">\r\n<div class="practice-area-col">\r\n<h3><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Outdoor-Advertising">Outdoor Advertising</a></h3>\r\n<p>Our advertising lawyers counsel and advise clients on the placement, control and transfer of all New York City outdoor advertising assets and the regulations governing them. Our attorneys are well known and respected by the city regulators and governing agencies that enforce and oversee all outdoor advertising activities. Our years of experience and strong knowledge of the outdoor advertising industry allow us to provide our clients valuable legal counsel and guidance, saving them time and money in an ever-changing market.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Outdoor-Advertising">Visit this practice area</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="practice-area-col">\r\n<h3><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Real-Estate-Law">Real Estate Law</a></h3>\r\n<p>Our New York real estate lawyers advise clients on every aspect of commercial and residential real estate transactions. We have experience representing all parties involved in varied real property asset classes including hotels and restaurants, office towers, shopping centers and stores, multi-family and multi-purpose buildings, condominium boards and cooperative corporations, industrial properties and warehouses. From sale and leasing, to financing and deal making, to special permits, variances and zoning, to disputes and litigation, we do it all from start to finish. Our years of experience, strong government relationships and knowledge of the New York real estate marketplace allow us to provide our clients with valuable legal counsel and guidance that is second to none.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Real-Estate-Law">Visit this practice area</a></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="practice-area-col-last">\r\n<h3><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Restaurant-and-Hospitality">Restaurant &amp; Hospitality</a></h3>\r\n<p>Our restaurant and hospitality lawyers are second to none in assisting clients in New York City and Long Island with all their legal business needs. Our attorneys represent restaurants, night clubs, fitness centers, hotels and other entertainment establishments. Our attorneys have years of experience and knowledge of these industries and strong relationships with local, State and Federal governmental agencies that license, govern and enforce their businesses. We are able to help owners and managers promptly and effectively cut through the red tape to meet their business objectives.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Restaurant-and-Hospitality">Visit this practice area</a></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="clear">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class="practice-areas-grid">\r\n<div class="practice-area-col">\r\n<h3><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Trusts-and-Estates-Law">Trusts &amp; Estates Law</a></h3>\r\n<p>Our Trusts and Estates lawyers represent individuals and business owners in all aspects of their estate planning needs, from wills and trusts, to gift giving and charitable foundations, to health care plans and power of attorney, to succession planning and special needs. Our attorneys follow Federal and State tax law changes that affect estate planning. We pride ourselves on working with clients to develop customized wills and estate plans to protect, preserve and transfer assets. We are also experienced in tax and estate related litigation matters and in representing clients before the Internal Revenue Service.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../law-practice-areas/Trusts-and-Estates-Law">Visit this practice area</a></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>', 'Law Practice Areas', 0x4c6177205072616374696365204172656173, 1, 1, 0, 1, 'Law-Practice-Areas', 3, ''),
(102, 2, 0, 'Sid Davidoff Quoted in The New York Times', '', '2013-04-17 00:00:00', '2013-04-18 11:12:37', '<p><span class="userContent">Sid Davidoff, Senior Partner at our Firm, and former administrative assistant for Mayor John Lindsay, sheds light on how Henry Francis, the <a href="https://www.facebook.com/MadMen?group_id=0" data-hovercard="/ajax/hovercard/page.php?id=140731500326&amp;extragetparams=%7B%22group_id%22%3A0%7D">Mad Men</a> character who serves as Mayor Lindsay''s senior aide (and pictured below), is able to live in a Westchester-based mansion desipite perceived residency requirements for city officials, in this article appearing in <a id="js_11" href="https://www.facebook.com/nytimes?group_id=0" data-hovercard="/ajax/hovercard/page.php?id=5281959998&amp;extragetparams=%7B%22group_id%22%3A0%7D">The New York Times</a>. <a href="http://nyti.ms/XEtPGa" rel="nofollow nofollow" target="_blank">http://nyti.ms/XEtPGa</a></span></p>', 'sid davidoff, mad men, new york times', '', 0, 1, 1, 1, 'Sid-Davidoff-Quoted-in-The-New-York-Times', 0, ''),
(44, 2, 0, 'Thomas P. Mohen joined Davidoff Hutcher & Citron as a partner.', '', '2012-10-26 00:00:00', '2012-10-27 11:29:24', '<p>Thomas P. Mohen joined Davidoff Hutcher &amp; Citron as a partner. Based in the law and government relations firm''s Garden City and Manhattan offices, Mohen applies more than 25 years of practice in general business matters, employment law and commercial litigation. He was formerly a partner in Mohen &amp; Treacy of Manhattan and Locust Valley.</p>', 'asdfsadf', 0x617364667364, 0, 1, 1, 1, 'Thomas-P--Mohen-joined-Davidoff-Hutcher---Citron-as-a-partner-', 0, ''),
(45, 2, 0, 'How to protect your money in divorce', '', '2012-10-26 00:00:00', '2012-10-25 20:05:21', '<p>Divorce is devastating. Not only are you broken hearted, but without careful planning you can also wind up broke. The stakes are higher still if you''re in the 50+ club when you part ways. Increasingly, divorce is a reality for the grey-hair set.</p>\r\n<p>"I am seeing couples divorce in their 70s. They do not have the advantage of building up their retirement. They have to live on what they already have socked away," says Tracy Stewart, a certified public accountant who specializes in divorce.</p>', 'sdf', 0x6466, 0, 1, 1, 1, 'How-to-protect-your-money-in-divorce', 0, ''),
(46, 3, 0, 'DAVIDOFF MALITO & HUTCHER LLP RENAMED AS DAVIDOFF HUTCHER & CITRON LLP', '', '2012-02-28 01:41:55', '2012-11-30 10:56:51', '<p>NEW YORK, June 4, 2012 - Davidoff Malito &amp; Hutcher LLP, one of New York''s top law and government affairs firms, announced today it has changed its name to Davidoff Hutcher &amp; Citron LLP.</p>\r\n<p>INSERT INTO `articles3` (`id`, `article_type_id`, `category_id`, `article_name`, `link_title`, `created`, `modified`, `content`, `keywords`, `description`, `article_template_id`, `user_id`, `news_type_id`, `modified_by`, `url`, `position`, `pagetitle`) VALUES
(58, 2, 0, 'Kramer.com vs. Kramer.com', '', '2012-11-29 00:00:00', '2012-11-30 09:35:22', '<p>MOST divorced couples would probably prefer not to see each other. Ever again. But when you share custody of your children, you have to assume a certain amount of face-to-face time amid the endless back-and-forthing.</p>\r\n<p>Think of the clashing summer vacation plans, the who-goes-to-Lucy''s-birthday-party, the "Max forgot his homework again" at Dad''s. And those devilish contretemps that can arise if Mom, for example, decides to keep her house kosher while Dad serves the children pork chops. Or if her new boyfriend is suddenly sleeping over on "her" nights to host the children.</p>\r\n<p>Let''s just say that no matter how well ex-spouses and still-parents coordinate, there''s a good chance of teary phone calls, angry exchanges during drop-off, and all-out fights about who''s not saving enough for college, often played out smack in front of the children.</p>\r\n<p>Unless, of course, it''s all done remotely. These days, the cool aloofness of technology is helping temper sticky emotional exchanges between former spouses. And for the most part, according to divorce lawyers and joint-custody bearers, handling the details via high tech is a serious upgrade.</p>\r\n<p>It''s joint custody &mdash; at a distance.</p>\r\n<p>And it makes a big difference. Like many engaged women, Erin McGillivray, 26, broke up with her fianc&eacute; before they could marry. But unlike many engaged women, she also got pregnant. By the time the two split, their daughter was 8 months old. And now they''re tied by the bonds of parenthood for the rest of their lives.</p>\r\n<p>Ms. McGillivray, a wardrobe stylist in Minneapolis, became mired in a custody dispute with her ex over their daughter, now 2. (The court eventually awarded her joint legal and primary physical custody.)</p>\r\n<p>"Normally, when you break up with someone, you don''t have to see them constantly," Ms. McGillivray said. "Now I have to see my ex and his current fianc&eacute;e several times a week. He''ll be a presence in my life for at least 17 more years, and probably more than that."</p>\r\n<p>When they see each other in person, she said, they inevitably quarrel. And so she keeps him at a safe electronic remove. "When it comes to child arrangements," she said, "we typically communicate via e-mail. Schedules, drop-offs, pickups, sick-day care: it''s all done electronically. Neither of us wants to argue in front of our daughter, but as much as we would want to avoid it, it would happen."</p>\r\n<p>It''s not surprising that most people don''t see eye-to-eye with the person they left seething on a couples therapist''s sofa. If you didn''t get along with someone well enough to stay married, chances are you will probably disagree after you divorce.</p>\r\n<p>"People don''t want to talk to their exes because just the sound of their voice is irritating," said Randy Kessler, chair of the American Bar Association''s Family Law Section and a matrimonial lawyer in Atlanta. "But they can e-mail. They can share an online calendar. They can use any number of resources on the Internet. There are even divorce apps."</p>\r\n<p>E-mail and texting alone have practically revolutionized postdivorce family relationships. "E-mail absolutely takes away the in-your-face aggravation and emotional side of joint custody," said Lubov Stark, a divorce lawyer on the Upper East Side of Manhattan. "You just write, ''I want to pick up Kimmy at 5, but I''m running late and will be there at 6.'' It''s the best thing ever."</p>\r\n<p>When Zeita Jones, a 39-year-old nurse in Los Angeles, divorced her husband of 15 years in 2010, dealing with her ex while shuffling their three children every week was difficult. "When emotions were running high at the beginning, everything was e-mail and text," Ms. Jones said. "It''s a lot easier not hearing the voice. It''s detached."</p>\r\n<p>For Cheryl Wu, a 34-year-old Manhattan pediatrician, nailing down details on a Google calendar makes all the difference. First, she and her ex-husband, who have joint legal custody (she has primary physical custody) of their 5-year-old son, will e-mail each other possible arrangements until they reach a point of agreement. Once there, it goes into the mutual calendar. Since the two separated in 2010, they have only had to talk face-to-face two or three times.</p>\r\n<p>"Everything on our calendar is jointly shared, so there''s no dispute," Ms. Wu said. "For a while, I was doing all the entering of events, but I told him to put his share in, too, and now it''s all on there."</p>\r\n<p>Such arrangements are increasingly necessary. Unlike the "Kramer vs. Kramer" 1970s, when mothers won primary custody almost by default, today''s postdivorce "bi-nuclear family" setups are more egalitarian. Almost all states now offer some kind of joint custody. Joint legal custody, in which parents share or split decision-making, is almost the norm. And while laws vary widely by state, joint physical custody, where children divide their time between their father''s and mother''s homes, is increasingly common.</p>\r\n<p>"In the ''80s, you used to see Dad on Sundays and get a Happy Meal and an ice cream cone," said Leslie Barbara, a partner in the matrimonial and family law department at Davidoff Hutcher &amp; Citron in Manhattan. "Now it''s all gender-neutral, and the parents each get spheres of influence. You put together what''s called an ''access schedule,'' and ''parenting coordinators'' help figure it all out."</p>\r\n<p>Former spouses aren''t the only parties to see a benefit in keeping their communiqu&eacute;s limited to the keyboard. Technology has become so commonplace in divorce arrangements that it has become part of the formal legal process, a development divorce lawyers and judges applaud. Many joint custody arrangements will stipulate weekly Skype sessions between parent and child while apart.</p>\r\n<p>"It''s all set out in detail," said Michael Kelly, a divorce lawyer and partner at Kelly, Fernandez &amp; Karney in Los Angeles. "Your phone has to be available at certain hours, and if you don''t follow the rules, it''s a good way to lose custody."</p>\r\n<p>Parents are often required to buy a cellphone for their child, and call times are recorded to ensure an adequate amount of time. "That way, Mom can''t say, ''O.K., you can talk to Daddy for two minutes, but that''s it,'' " Mr. Kelly said. And with a parent calling children directly on their phone, there''s no possibility of a bitter intermediary exchange between parent and parent.</p>\r\n<p>When relationships deteriorate to the point of renewed legal action, courts are increasingly ordering ex-couples to work out their differences via technology. A new crop of online custody tools has been specifically designed to keep sniping parents at bay.</p>\r\n<p>Sherry Thomas, 56, shares physical custody of her two teenage sons with her ex-husband in Boca Raton, Fla. But since their divorce in 2005, the arrangement has been fraught with disagreement. When Ms. Thomas requested court-mandated parent counseling, the judge ordered the two to use an online tool called Our Family Wizard instead. Now, lawyers supervise e-mail exchanges between her and her ex, ensuring that each party responds to the other in a timely manner. All e-mails are time dated and tracked. Parents can create a shared expense log and receive automated notices and reminders about parental obligations.</p>\r\n<p>"It''s a very good idea," Ms. Thomas said. "Of course, provided both parents use it. Otherwise you can just end up back in court again."</p>\r\n<p>Many see the Wizard and similar online custody management tools as a postmarriage savior, especially after old-fashioned conversation has failed. In certain highly contentious divorces, parents are expressly forbidden to use the phone unless a child has broken a leg on the tricycle or some other emergency.</p>\r\n<p>"The most hostile couples I see are the ones using the Wizard, and I think in those cases nothing would get done without it," said Fran Walfish, a Beverly Hills-based psychotherapist. "They wouldn''t have any other means of communicating if it weren''t online."</p>\r\n<p>Having negotiations set in writing (whether it''s a text, a cellphone log or an online calendar) also creates a permanent record of who did and wrote what. If somebody misbehaves, it can become evidence.</p>\r\n<p>Pam Abrams, a 54-year-old freelance writer in Manhattan, had an amicable lawyer-free divorce in 2006. But over time, relations with her ex, with whom she shares custody of two children, frayed. There have been times the two could barely speak to each other. Money was a near-constant source of tension. "When we weren''t getting along, everything was arranged by text," she said.</p>\r\n<p>But as anyone who has ever quarreled electronically knows, keyboarded messages can nonetheless get testy. Humor, irony, sarcasm and even genuine kindness get lost in the cloud. Not every nuance carries over in a hastily tapped text. And people don''t answer e-mails from their ex-husbands the same way people don''t answer e-mails from anyone they don''t feel like corresponding with. "There was a moment when things were so acrimonious, I didn''t want to be textable or e-mailable at all," Ms. Abrams recalled. Now where is the technology that can solve that?</p>', 'divorced couples, divorce lawyer ', , 0, 1, 1, 1, 'Kramer-com-vs--Kramer-com', 0, ''),
(59, 2, 0, 'DC Update', '', '2012-11-30 00:00:00', '2012-11-30 20:44:32', '<p>On behalf of our clients, we attended the hearing yesterday of the Senate Committee on Environment and Public Works, chaired by Senator Barbara Boxer (D-CA) titled &ldquo;Sandy and its impacts: a local perspective.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>All witnesses were Senators or House members from States and Districts affected by Sandy.&nbsp; Several Senators making presentations were members of the Committee itself, including&nbsp; Lautenberg ( D-NJ ), Gillibrand (D-NY), Carper (D-DE), Whitehouse (D-RI), Cardin (D-MD.)&nbsp; Senator David Vitter (R-LA), the only Minority member attending, made clear that he considered issues related to the Superstorm Sandy had to be considered by Congress on a bipartisan basis.</p>\r\n<p>In general, these Committee members and other Congressional witnesses, including Senators Schumer (D-NY) and Menendez (D-NJ) offered detailed reviews, sometimes emotionally, of the severe damage their states had suffered.&nbsp; &ldquo;Invest in mitigation now or pay later in the next storm&rdquo; was a common theme.</p>\r\n<p>The pace of activity relating to funding is picking up, but Congress is still awaiting word from the White House on the size of the initial request for supplemental appropriations.&nbsp; In the hearing, Senator Schumer said that he expected the request to be submitted early in the week of December 2nd and would include substantial funding and provisions to ease some restrictions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Several of the Congressional witnesses at the hearing urged availability of direct grants for small businesses from the SBA and other agencies.&nbsp; Congressman Pascrell (D-NJ) broke news when he announced that the House Ways and Means Committee will be working on legislation that would provide direct grants for small businesses affected by natural disasters.&nbsp; Several members agreed that many small businesses do not have the capacity to meet the SBA&rsquo;s onerous requirements and pay its reduced interest rate.</p>\r\n<p>Senator Saxby Chambliss (R-GA) has raised the matter of offsets to the aid packages, to include matching cuts in other areas of the federal budget, but Senate Majority Leader Reid has stated that he does not expect to have a confrontation with GOP members over this and those sentiments were echoed by both Democrats and Republicans at yesterday&rsquo;s hearing.</p>\r\n<p>There will be two more Congressional hearings next week which we will attend.&nbsp; On December 4, the full House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure (Mica R-FL, Chair) will hold a hearing on &ldquo;Review of Preparedness, Response and Recovery from Hurricane Sandy&rdquo; and on December 6, the Senate Commerce Committee&rsquo;s Surface Transportation Subcommittee (Lautenberg D-NJ Chair) will review &ldquo;The Devastating Impact of Superstorm Sandy on the Nation&rsquo;s Largest Transportation Systems.&rdquo;<br />Next week we will be continuing to brief members and staff of the New York and New Jersey Delegations and especially those on the House Appropriations Committee, to inform them of our clients concerns.&nbsp; We want to make sure that in our individual meetings, we explain the need for alternative funding and direct grants for businesses that were hardest hit by Hurricane Sandy. We will continue to keep you updated on our progress. <br />&nbsp;<br />Russ Klenet, Steve Slade &amp; Jonathan McCollum <br />Davidoff Hutcher and Citron LLP<br />Federal Government Relations Office<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>', 'dc lawyers, district of columbia lawyers', , 0, 1, 1, 1, 'DC-Update', 0, ''),
(65, 2, 0, 'Democrats Seek GOP Support for Monday Disaster Aid Vote', '', '2012-12-14 00:00:00', '2012-12-17 07:35:45', '<p>Senate Democrats believe they can marshal enough GOP support to pass a wide-ranging $60.4 billion Superstorm Sandy recovery package that would go far beyond simply addressing the immediate needs of hard-hit communities.</p>\r\n<p><span><span class="person-ref"><a id="wicket-generated-id-103" href="http://www.cq.com/person/371">Charles E. Schumer</a></span></span> of New York, the No. 3 Democrat in the Senate, said he is &ldquo;hopeful&rdquo; of getting needed GOP support for the bill, which might be brought up in the chamber Monday. The measure likely will face a procedural motion requiring 60 votes for it to proceed.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;We&rsquo;re working on Republicans,&rdquo; Schumer told reporters Thursday. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re not there yet, that&rsquo;s for sure.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Senate Majority Leader <span><span class="person-ref"><a id="wicket-generated-id-104" href="http://www.cq.com/person/337">Harry Reid</a></span></span>, D-Nev., said work was under way to reach a deal Thursday afternoon to be able to take up the emergency spending bill Monday.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;We hope that . . . we&rsquo;ll be in a position to enter an order that we would move to&rdquo; the spending package, Reid said. He added that the Senate could convene earlier than normal Monday in order to begin debate on the measure.</p>\r\n<p>Many Republicans have argued that Congress should move more slowly in response to Sandy and should also seek cuts in other federal programs to pay for at least some of the relief expenses. Schumer and other Democrats have argued that a &ldquo;robust&rdquo; and immediate approach is needed, allowing federal agencies, states, towns, small businesses and homeowners to begin responding to the destruction caused by the storm. They oppose including offsets for this spending.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Every senator, no matter what their party, ought to think about what will happen if a disaster strikes their area,&rdquo; Schumer said.</p>\r\n<p>Many Republicans already are indicating that the Sandy package may need to be scaled back, particularly in terms of long-term mitigation projects. <span><span class="person-ref"><a id="wicket-generated-id-105" href="http://www.cq.com/person/7122">Lamar Alexander</a></span></span>, R-Tenn., who has been supportive of emergency Sandy aid, questions the need to quickly provide about $13 billion for projects to reduce future flood risks, which he said may be more appropriately funded through the annual appropriations process.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;That&rsquo;s not necessarily a part of dealing with emergency damage to victims of Hurricane Sandy in the next four or five months,&rdquo; said Alexander, who is the ranking Republican on the Appropriations panel that funds the Army Corps of Engineers. &ldquo;So that may not be a part of this bill.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p><span><span class="person-ref"><a id="wicket-generated-id-106" href="http://www.cq.com/person/17262">Lisa Murkowski</a></span></span> of Alaska, the ranking Republican on the Interior-Environment Appropriations subcommittee, whose panel also is examining the draft bill, said she sees the bill&rsquo;s proposed mitigation spending as being &ldquo;in excess of the request for immediate relief.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;What is a must-have . . . in this fiscal year? What is going to be nice to have, and can it be rolled into the regular budget process?&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p><span><span class="person-ref"><a id="wicket-generated-id-107" href="http://www.cq.com/person/14833">John Cornyn</a></span></span> of Texas, who will be the Senate GOP minority whip in the 113th session of Congress, questioned the need to immediately appropriate funds that won&rsquo;t be spent for many years. According to a Congressional Budget Office estimate, about $15 billion of the money to be provided by the Senate bill would be spent between the year beginning Oct. 1, 2016, and the year ending Sept. 30, 2022.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;By definition, it&rsquo;s not an emergency if it&rsquo;s needed 10 years from now,&rdquo; Cornyn said. &ldquo;It could be handled with the regular course of business through the appropriations process.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Even Republicans whose own states are frequent victims of hurricanes have reservations about the pending Senate bill.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Being from Florida, I anticipate that one day, unfortunately, we may have another storm of that sort of magnitude. So we definitely want to get them help, but at the same time, I want to see what&rsquo;s in it,&rdquo; said <span><span class="person-ref"><a id="wicket-generated-id-108" href="http://www.cq.com/person/32335">Marco Rubio</a></span></span>, R-Fla. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s got to be reasonable and storm-related. I want to make sure that there are not things in there that don&rsquo;t belong.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>The Senate Appropriations Committee measure released Wednesday is intended to pump money immediately into programs that will quickly funnel aid to people who suffered losses from the late October storm, and to allocate billions to allow for long-term planning on major projects to begin immediately.</p>\r\n<p>If the Senate bill is enacted, only about $8.97 billion would be spent in the current budget year, which ends Sept. 30, 2013, according to CBO. More than half of this, $5.3 billion, represents expected outlays from the National Flood Insurance Program. Another $1.2 billion of expected actual fiscal 2013 spending would come from the Federal Emergency Management Agency&rsquo;s Disaster Relief Fund.</p>\r\n<p>A key driver of this spending would be the Community Development Fund, which the Senate bill envisions as a flexible tool to allow communities to address a wide variety of needs, such as restoring damaged housing. Spending from that account would jump to $3.4 billion in fiscal 2014 from $75 million in fiscal 2013. Fiscal 2015 spending would represent a peak for this program, with the CBO seeing $3.8 billion spent.</p>\r\n<p>Schumer said the advance funding is critical to the recovery effort. &ldquo;If a locality is going to rebuild a road or tunnel, they need to know that the money is there to sign the contract, to know that they will be reimbursed,&rdquo; Schumer said. &ldquo;You can&rsquo;t say, &lsquo;We&rsquo;ll fix a large tunnel, the Brooklyn Battery Tunnel. We&rsquo;ll fix the tunnel, about a half a mile of it this year, and then we&rsquo;ll see if we can get the money next year.&rsquo;&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Schumer also said CBO may be looking at what happened after 2005&rsquo;s Hurricane Katrina as the model, but in that catastrophe, many people didn&rsquo;t return home and begin seeking federal aid to rebuild homes for many months.</p>\r\n<p>In general, the Senate bill closely resembles the White House&rsquo;s $60.4 billion request made on Dec. 7, but it adds some new spending not specifically mentioned in the Obama administration&rsquo;s proposal. Included would be $125 million for a Department of Agriculture watershed program that could help Colorado cope with the aftermath of the summer&rsquo;s wildfires and $50 million for the National Parks Service&rsquo;s Historic Preservation Fund. The Sandy bill also would include $150 million for fisheries that have faced recent disasters in Alaska and the Gulf of Mexico, as well as New England, said <span><span class="person-ref"><a id="wicket-generated-id-109" href="http://www.cq.com/person/29230">Mark Begich</a></span></span>, D-Alaska, who had sought this funding to address the marine debris washing up on the coasts of Western states from the Japan earthquake of March 2011.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The failure of Chinook returns in 2010, 2011 and 2012 had a devastating impact on commercial and subsistence fisheries in Alaska,&rdquo; Begich said in a written statement. &ldquo;These much-needed funds will help make communities whole and hopefully help fund research on factors affecting Chinook returns.&rdquo;</p>', 'Disaster Aid', '', 0, 1, 1, 1, 'Democrats-Seek-GOP-Support-for-Monday-Disaster-Aid-Vote', 0, ''),
