(90, 2, 0, 'Sid Davidoff about what it meant to be on Nixonâ€™s list for Common Cause March 13-14, 2013 Event', '', '2013-02-14 00:00:00', '2013-02-14 15:24:33', '<p>I served as New York City Mayor John V. Lindsay&rsquo;s chief administrative assistant from 1966 to 1973.&nbsp; In this role, I served as Lindsay&rsquo;s right-hand-man and chief political operative.&nbsp; After leaving City government, I co-owned, &ldquo;Jimmy&rsquo;s Restaurant&rdquo; located on West 52<sup>nd</sup> Street, which was named after newspaper legend Jimmy Breslin who was also slated to be a partner. &nbsp;That fateful day when I learned that I was on Nixon&rsquo;s &ldquo;Opponents and Political Enemies List,&rdquo; started just like any other.&nbsp; The din of restaurant chatter was punctuated by the sudden barrage of phone calls. Simultaneously, people at the bar started yelling &ldquo;Hey Sid, you are on TV!&rdquo;&nbsp; This was a result of the news reporting on John Dean&rsquo;s testimony before Congress making the list public.&nbsp; That served as my wake-up call and introduction to Nixon&rsquo;s &ldquo;Opponents and Political Enemies List.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>That day my name and face was plastered all over the television and it seemed like every reporter in the Metro area was calling my restaurant.&nbsp; Jimmy Breslin, with his insider status in the newspaper industry, was able to get the scoop on what was transpiring and called me right away to allay any confusion that I might have had in those initial frenzied hours.&nbsp;&nbsp; I gave Breslin an exclusive interview and was busy sharing my story with other outlets in the coming days.&nbsp;&nbsp; In the midst of the media feeding frenzy, I figured there was no better time than now to celebrate my newfound status by hosting an &ldquo;Enemies Ball&rdquo; that Saturday night at Jimmy&rsquo;s.&nbsp; There was a lot of fun and excitement around it.</p>\r\n<p>However, despite the thrill of being included on Nixon&rsquo;s enemies list with fellow major political opponents, I soon found that there were ramifications associated with being included on the list as well.&nbsp; As a consequence of being on the list, I was audited by the IRS and constantly under investigation by Nixon operatives.&nbsp; The fallout was significant, taking me more than several years to unravel the damage that had been caused due to the heightened scrutiny stemming from Nixon&rsquo;s &ldquo;Opponents and Political Enemies List.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>I subsequently exited the restaurant business in 1975 and started a successful law and lobbying firm that bears my name, Davidoff, Hutcher &amp; Citron LLP.&nbsp; Today, the firm, based in New York City, has over 50 attorneys with offices in Albany and Garden City, NY and Washington DC.&nbsp; The firm is commonly recognized as one of New York''s most respected mid-size commercial law and government relations firms.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>To be included on that list of great Americans from Paul Newman to journalist Daniel Schorr turned out to be a badge of honor for me as, I believe it was for them and for most of the people on that list. Interestingly, despite everything I&rsquo;ve accomplished since then in city and state government, it&rsquo;s my inclusion on &ldquo;Nixon&rsquo;s Enemies List&rdquo; that everyone I meet still wants to ask me about. Well, that and what it was like to play Carmela&rsquo;s divorce lawyer on &ldquo;The Sopranos.&rdquo;</p>', 'government relations lawyer new york', 0x4d617263682031332d31342c2032303133204576656e74, 0, 1, 1, 1, 'Sid-Davidoff-about-what-it-meant-to-be-on-Nixonâ€™s-list-for-Common-Cause-March-13-14,-2013-Event', 0, 'March 13-14, 2013 Event');
